<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182006" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole allarmata Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole allarmata Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="allarmata">Pheidole allarmata</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="649">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">
etymology Gr, L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182006" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole allarmata Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole allarmata Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="allarmata">allarmata</taxonomicName>
, the &quot;other one&quot; bearing arms, referring to the species' similarity to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34032" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subarmata">subarmata</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182084" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole synarmata Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole synarmata Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="synarmata">synarmata</taxonomicName>
. diagnosis Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182041" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole hasticeps Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole hasticeps Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hasticeps">hasticeps</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34032" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subarmata">subarmata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182084" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole synarmata Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole synarmata Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="synarmata">synarmata</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182088" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole triplex Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole triplex Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplex">triplex</taxonomicName>
(see also the somewhat less similar 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:182070" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole rhytifera Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole rhytifera Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rhytifera">rhytifera</taxonomicName>
), differing from these and other 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole Westwood" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of traits.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">Major: in side view the frontal lobe is elongated to form a forward-projecting, thin, spine-like lobe; humerus strongly developed as protuberant lobes; postpetiolar node spinose; head quadrate; rear half of head and almost all of body smooth and shiny. Minor: occiput narrowed but lacking a nuchal collar; propodeal spine long, thin, and erect; head and body almost entirely smooth and shiny.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">
This is probably the series noted by W. L. Brown (1981: 526) as representing a species distinct from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34032" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole subarmata Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="649" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subarmata">subarmata</taxonomicName>
. measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 1.26, HL 1.28, SL 0.60, EL 0.12, PW 0.74. Paratype minor: HW 0.56, HL 0.56, SL 0.60, EL 0.06, PW 0.36.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="649">Color Major: head reddish brown, gradually deepening from light reddish brown at occiput to dark reddish brown on anterior half of head capsule and on mandibles; mesosoma medium reddish brown; waist, gaster, antennae, and legs light reddish brown. Minor: concolorous yellow to dark brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">Range An Amazonian species recorded from scattered localities in Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Suriname.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="649">Biology Two colonies collected by Stefan Cover and John E. Tobin at Cuzco Amazonico, Peru (Cover, collection notes) were in terra firme rainforest, nesting in rotten sticks on the forest floor. The colonies were small, with fewer than 100 workers and a single queen; one of the nests contained a seed cache.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
